text:
@SciencePundit @zimmerdiamonds @pgliljedahl @Mathowitz @Mathgarden @dexterlearning I record results on a whiteboard.
9 and 4 is 23
7 and 3 is 11
7 and 4 is 17
11 and 5 is 39
9 and 6 you can’t do
Etc.

And eventually someone comes up with the formula.
And we talk about why it works for some and not others.

9/n

@SciencePundit @zimmerdiamonds @pgliljedahl @Mathowitz @Mathgarden @dexterlearning Without getting into Strategies-I offer hints.
When a group can explain why they have the largest number you can’t get-and they can get every number after-I offer up different dartboards.
What if
7 and 3
7 and 4
11 and 4
9 and 6
9 and 5
8 and 4
And so on
8/n

@SciencePundit @zimmerdiamonds @pgliljedahl @Mathowitz @Mathgarden @dexterlearning S ponders.
I am like throw your first dart. 🎯 
S throws-I am like “what did you get?”
S says 9.
Ok throw your second dart. There is mumbling in the background from other S’s.
Finally “S can’t get 15”
I am like “ you can’t get 15? Can you?”
Discussion why?

Then the bomb! 6/n

u cross v=|u||v|sin theta e hat

Proceeded to derive the algebraic definition of the cross product.

9/n

text:
My 4th question was “pick two non-collinear vectors with no zero components then find a vector perpendicular to both.”

This was tough. Lots of answers that didn’t check out (using the dot product).

Lots of struggle.

Eventually some groups had a vector that worked.

6/n

Round 3

What is the cheapest way to package 96 golf balls?

After exploring S’s decided on 4 by 4 by 6 - “most cubey” - packages 96 golf balls exactly.

4 by 4 by 6 cost $1.15
5 by 5 by 4 cost $1.17
